<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1870-10-03T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1870-10-03T00:00:00-05:00" n="167" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d167">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">No. 167.</note>
                        <head><persName type="from">Mr. Bancroft</persName> to <persName type="to">Mr. Fish</persName>.</head>
                        <opener>
                            <seg rendition="#left"><hi rend="smallcaps">No. 146.]</hi></seg>
                            <dateline rendition="#right">
                                <placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">American Legation,</hi><hi rend="italic"> Berlin</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1870-10-03"><hi rend="italic">October</hi> 3, 1870</date>. (Received October
                                20.)</dateline></opener>
                        <p><hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: I have this moment received, a little in
                            advance of the press, a lithographic copy of Count Bismarck’s account of
                            his interview with Jules Favre. Having no time to make a translation or
                            abstract of it before the closing of the mail, I send you the document
                            as I received it from the Foreign Office.</p>
                        <p rend="center">* * * * * * * *</p>
                        <closer>
                            <signed>GEO. BANCROFT.</signed></closer>
                        <postscript>
                            <p>[For a translation of this inclosure see Baron Gerolt’s note to Mr.
                                Fish of October 17, 1870, <hi rend="italic">post</hi>.]</p>
                        </postscript>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>